I found that it won't be able to effectively show the characteristic of polymorphism if I just call the instance, here is the modified code of AlarmChecker::checkAlarm():
```
switch(alarmType)     
{
    case AlarmType::hardShutdown:
    case AlarmType::softShutdown:
        ProtectionAlarmHandler(alarms, alarmType, _powerState)
            .checkAlarm(sensorPath, properties);
    case AlarmType::critical:
    case AlarmType::warning:
        RecoveryAlarmHandler(alarms, alarmType)
            .checkAlarm(sensorPath, properties);
}
```

If I keep the type convertion (i.e., keep obtainAlarmHandler() or just squash it into AlarmChecker::checkAlarm), I only need to modify the code of instance allocation when there is a new AlarmHandler is extended, and the code can clearly express that the AlarmsHandlers are sibling.

Surely I will change the type from shared_ptr to unique_ptr. What do you think about this?

*P.s. The demo code of "squash obtainAlarmHandler() into AlarmChecker::checkAlarm"*
```
std::unique_ptr<AlarmHandler> alarmHandler;

switch (alarmType)
{
    case AlarmType::hardShutdown:
    case AlarmType::softShutdown:
        alarmHandler = std::make_unique<ProtectionAlarmHandler>(alarms, alarmType,
                                                        _powerState);
    case AlarmType::critical:
    case AlarmType::warning:
        alarmHandler = std::make_unique<RecoveryAlarmHandler>(alarms, alarmType);
    default:
        throw std::runtime_error("Unsupported alarmType");
}

alarmHandler->checkAlarm(sensorPath, properties);
```

